            }
            //need another for loop to see which value is missing
            for (int i = 0; i &lt; 10; i++)
            {
                if (!foundValues[i])
                {
                    return i;
                }
            }
        return -1; 
  }
```
should just work.

Java doesn&#39;t know that exactly one value is missing.
So you need to cover the case when none is missing. In this case the classic approach would be to return `-1`. However you could also throw an Exeption.
This method only returns the lowest missing value because it returns after that.

Another problem with this code is, that you are not checking if `0` is missing in the second for-loop. The above code does.

Alternatively you can use following code for the last part (returns `9` if no missing value found):
```java
//need another for loop to see which value is missing
for (int i = 0; i &lt; 10; i++)
{
    index = i;
    if (!foundValues[i])
    {
       break;
    }
}
return index; 
```
I wasn&#39;t quite sure what you want to achive reading your question.

So the code works as is. That&#39;s not the problem. The problem is that you have to do:

     for (int i = 1; i &lt; 10; i++)
     {
         if (!foundValues[i] == true)
         {
             index = i;                   
         }
     }

And then return the index, instead of just doing:

     for (int i = 1; i &lt; 10; i++)
     {
         if (!foundValues[i] == true)
         {
             return i;
         }
     }

The reason is pretty simple. The compiler have NO IDEA what&#39;s going to be in that array. What happens if you get say, an empty array? That&#39;s perfectly legal according to what you&#39;ve told the compiler. If you do that, you&#39;ll not get a hit on *any* index, and there will be no return statement. What should be returned then? There&#39;s no telling.

Therefore the compiler refuses to compile, because the code you&#39;ve written cannot guarantee that it&#39;ll return anything. But if you put a variable outside the loop, initialize it to 0, run the loop, and then return the variable, you&#39;re guaranteed to return a proper value.

Now a thing you could do if you wanted to is to throw an exception if you get past the loop. You&#39;re never supposed to get out of the loop, so it&#39;s an error. It would be as simple as:

    for (int i = 1; i &lt; 10; i++) {
        if (!foundValues[i] == true) {
            return i;
        }
    }
    throw new IllegalStateException(&quot;Cannot find any missing digit, so we have an error in our input.&quot;);

That way, the compiler is satisfied: If it finds something in the loop, it returns, and if it doesn&#39;t, it throws an exception, which it is also okay with.

